    <%# Ad: in_results %>
    <%= render "shared/calculator_rating", slug: "swim-pace" %>
    <div class="mb-8"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_results" %></div>

    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How the Swim Pace Calculator Works</h2>
      <p>
        Enter any swim distance and time to calculate your pace per 100 meters and 100 yards. The calculator also estimates your times for standard competitive distances from 50m through 1500m, applying fatigue factors that account for the natural pace slowdown that occurs over longer distances. Results update in real time as you type, with automatic conversion between meters and yards.
      </p>
      <p>
        Knowing your swim pace is essential for structured training, race planning, and tracking improvement over time. Swimmers in all disciplines use pace per 100 as the standard unit of measurement, similar to how runners use pace per kilometer or mile. By establishing your current pace, you can set realistic interval targets, plan race strategy, and monitor fitness gains throughout a training cycle.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding Swim Paces</h2>
      <p>
        Swim pace is expressed as time per 100 meters or 100 yards. A pace of 1:45/100m means it takes 1 minute and 45 seconds to cover 100 meters. Because 100 yards is shorter than 100 meters (by about 8.6%), your per-100y time will always be faster than your per-100m time at the same effort. The calculator handles this conversion automatically.
      </p>

      <h3>Distance Estimation and Fatigue Factors</h3>
      <p>
        The calculator estimates times for other distances by applying scientifically-based fatigue factors to your base pace. Sprint distances (50m) use about 92% of your base pace due to higher intensity, while longer distances apply increasing slowdown factors. For example, a 1500m estimate uses approximately 106% of your 400m pace. These factors are averages and individual variation exists based on training background and stroke efficiency.
      </p>

      <h3>Meters vs. Yards Pools</h3>
      <p>
        Short course yards (SCY) pools are 25 yards, short course meters (SCM) pools are 25 meters, and long course meters (LCM) pools are 50 meters. Times in SCY pools are fastest due to more turns (which provide push-off advantages) and shorter pool length. LCM times are slowest. When comparing times across pool types, conversion factors must account for both distance and turn differences.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How is swim pace calculated?</h3>
      <p>Divide total time by distance, then multiply by 100. A 400m swim in 8 minutes gives (480/400) x 100 = 120 seconds = 2:00/100m.</p>

      <h3>What is a good swim pace?</h3>
      <p>Recreational: 2:00-2:30/100m. Intermediate: 1:40-2:00. Advanced: under 1:20. Elite: 1:00-1:10/100m for middle distances.</p>

      <h3>How do you convert meters to yards?</h3>
      <p>Divide your per-100m pace by 1.09361 to get per-100y. Example: 2:00/100m equals about 1:50/100y.</p>

      <h3>Why are longer distance estimates slower?</h3>
      <p>Fatigue factors account for pace slowdown due to energy system limitations and muscle fatigue over increasing distances.</p>

      <h3>What is CSS?</h3>
      <p>Critical Swim Speed is your aerobic threshold pace, similar to FTP in cycling. It represents the fastest sustainable pace for aerobic training.</p>

    <%= render "shared/print_button" %>
